The behaviour as mentioned in an earlier reply to you is "mirroring" and it's typically used by individuals who have a false and a shaky sense of self and identity, whether they are aware of it or not. Often these behaviours are utilised by people who have antisocial personality disorder or APD for short which is the new umbrella term in the latest edition of the DSM, the book referred to by psychiatrists and psychologists as well as medical practitioners, and which refers to both psychopaths and sociopaths. These individuals will deliberately copy the behaviour they see in others from the emotional cues they perceive to body language because they personally don't have those emotions and don't understand them but in order to seem "normal", namely neurotypical, they'll do their best to mimic these and thereby try to 'pass' as "normal" so they 'fit in'.
